## Ownership Guard (Example)

```ts
@Injectable()
export class ResourceOwnerGuard implements CanActivate {
  constructor(private readonly userDb: UserDbService) {}

  async canActivate(context: ExecutionContext): Promise<boolean> {
    const req = context.switchToHttp().getRequest();
    const user = req.user;
    const resourceId = req.params.id;

    if (user.role === UserRole.SUPER_ADMIN) return true;

    const resource = await this.userDb.findById(resourceId);
    if (!resource || resource.userId !== user.id) {
      throw new ForbiddenException('Access denied');
    }

    return true;
  }
}
```

---

## Guard Application Order

Always apply guards in this order:

```ts
@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard, RolesGuard, ResourceOwnerGuard)
```

1. **JwtAuthGuard** â€” validates token, populates `req.user`
2. **RolesGuard** â€” checks role from `req.user`
3. **ResourceOwnerGuard** â€” checks resource ownership

---

## Rules

- Always combine `JwtAuthGuard` and `RolesGuard` on authenticated routes
- Guards must throw `UnauthorizedException` or `ForbiddenException` â€” never `ApiError`
- Never put business logic inside guards
- Guards can query the database for ownership checks only â€” never for business operations
- Apply guards at the class level where all routes share the same protection
- Override per-route with method-level decorators where needed

---

